article.headline: Georgia 100, Savannah State 69
article.story: ATHENS, Ga. (AP) -- Levi Stukes scored 23 points and Georgia pulled away early for a 100-69 victory over winless Savannah State Tuesday night. The win was the fifth straight for Georgia, which has not won that many consecutively since winning six in a row early in the 2001-2002 season. Alex Evans hit a 3-pointer at the buzzer as the Bulldogs reached the century mark for the first time since beating Coastal Carolina in December 2000, 102-69. Savannah State hung around until Kevin Brophy's 3-pointer started a 12-point streak by the Bulldogs (6-3) that pushed the lead to 45-26 when Sundiata Gaines converted a layup off a steal with 4:56 to go in the half. Gaines scored 13 for Georgia and Channing Toney 12. Coach Dennis Felton emptied his bench in playing 14 players, including freshman walk-on Brophy, who scored a career-high 11. Mark Williams led the Tigers (0-15) with 21 points. Donald Carson had 16 points and 11 rebounds. Three times in the opening minutes, Savannah State led by a point, the last time at 6-5 after Sherrard Reddick's putback with 17:56 to go in the half. But Georgia scored the next nine points, including three baskets by Stukes, to take a 14-6 lead at the 16:43 mark. Georgia led 55-36 at halftime, but the Tigers scored the first two baskets of the second half. However, any comeback hopes were quickly erased by a 12-2 Georgia run, capped by Brophy's steal and layup that made it 67-42 with 15:07 remaining. The final 31-point lead was the largest of the game.
